nomami dark shamans, religion and magic are re-evaluated not just from the practitioner’s perspective but through the victim’s lived experience. These original investigations reveal a nuanced approach to understanding social action, innovation, and the revitalization of tradition in colonial and post-colonial societies undergoing rapid social transformation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aMagic. 0aShamanism. 0aWar and society. 0aWarxReligious aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aChan, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarrer, D. S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarrer, Douglas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGrave, Jean-Marc de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJokic, Željko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeidel, J. David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoberts, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSellmann, James D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSinclair, Iain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311099822140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178533330940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781785333309423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781785333309/original  a978-3-11-099822-1  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPD